<TEXT>
the highly publicized soviet food shortage is most 
acute in big russian cities and seems milder in the countryside 
smaller cities and in nonrussian republics a survey indicates 
the situation is better here than in russia said povilas 
klimas deputy mayor of vilnius capital of the baltic republic of 
lithuania which declared independence in march were ready to 
go ahead on our own 
officials from the 12 cities surveyed by the associated press 
said there was more food in farmers markets than in state stores 
although prices were higher they blamed shortages on panicbuying 
and the collapse of the centralized distribution system which is 
not getting the harvest into cities 
president mikhail s gorbachev has appealed to the west for food 
to prevent winter unrest that he says may jeopardize his reforms 
foreign minister eduard shevardnadze carried the plea monday to 
secretary of state james a baker iii 
gorbachev has said that much of this years harvest has been 
diverted from the state distribution system and sold privately he 
has called upon the kgb security police to make sure that western 
food aid is not siphoned off 
an ap telephone survey found that food was plentiful in the 
baltic republics and central asia and scarce in russia and two 
republics hit by ethnic unrest armenia and moldavia 
the survey found little fear of starvation in keeping with more 
thorough public opinion polls conducted by soviet sociologists 
in a poll published this week in the weekly newspaper moscow 
news 27 percentbelieved that mass famine would commence this 
winter compared with 57 percent who thought it unlikely 
the poll of 1363 people by the union center for public opinion 
and market research found that 58 percent expected widespread 
strikes which could aggravate the food shortage 
the ap survey found that several soviet cities have rationed 
food but it appeared to do little good where supplies were scarce 
as in leningrad the secondlargest russian city 
leningrad officials are trying to bypass the state distribution 
system and buy directly from bettersupplied regions said 
lyudmilla smirnova a city government spokeswoman 
food is plentiful but rationed in nearby tallinn capital of 
estonia another breakaway baltic republic said mikhtel pilving 
head of the city council secretariat 
the monthly ration for butter is 11 pounds and 44 pounds each 
for sugar and grains pilving said 
yes we have ration cards for vodka and other alcoholic 
beverages he said 
food supplies are better than last year in the central asian 
republic of uzbekistan said yuri kukarin editor of the uzbek 
information agency 
there is a shortage of meat in state shops but a wide variety 
in the markets and there is no problem with dairy products and 
butter he said 
although uzbekistan has one of the lowest per capita incomes in 
the soviet union there has been no need to introduce rationing 
kukarin said 
we pray that the ration card infection does not spread to 
us he said the situation is definitely much better than 
in other regions in the countryside there are more fruits and 
vegetables 
food was also reported to be plentiful in the european republics 
of byelorussia and the ukraine and the caucasian republic of 
georgia 
officials in the ukrainian capital of kiev have prevented 
panicbuying by paying 70 percent of salaries in coupons that can 
be redeemed for specific products said mikhail derimov editor of 
the newspaper pravda ukraini 
but the situation sounded grim in armenia which has yet to 
recover from the earthquake of december 1988 and a civil war with 
azerbaijan 
how can you ration something when there is nothing to 
ration said karen mikaelyan aide to the yerevan city council 
member responsible for commerce in the armenian capital ration 
cards have been introduced for butter cereals sugar cheese 
tobacco and coffee 
food supplies were fair but prices were four times 1989 levels 
in kishinev the capital of moldavia which was hit by ethnic 
unrest last month said valery rinitse deputy editor of the 
vechernaya kishinev newspaper 
the city committee against sabotage has found that food 
supplies sent to state stores mysteriously disappear he said 
it is sold to speculators then taken out of the city to other 
regions or to other republics where they sell it at higher 
prices 
besides cracking down on theft moldavian officials have been 
trying to buy food from bettersupplied neighbors 
this year well be eating potatoes from poland said 
rinitse 
