<DOCNO> AP901211-0011 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
senior bush administration officials are 
considering suggestions ranging from a stiff gasoline tax to eased 
environmental rules as part of a blueprint for dealing with the 
nations future energy needs 
the national energy strategy has been in the works at the energy 
department for 18 months but it attracted increased attention 
after americas dependence on foreign oil was highlighted by the 
persian gulf crisis 
the department has put together 67 options for consideration by 
an interagency task force at the white house with a pareddown 
selection of proposals to be given president bush before christmas 
a draft energy plan is to be announced early next year 
many of the options already are under attack from 
environmentalists who say the administration is paying too little 
attention to energy conservation and too much attention to 
production at times at the risk of harming the environment 
theres no vision there is simply a long list of options 
christopher flavin an energy specialist at the worldwatch 
institute said of the proposals leaked so far 
all signs point to a policy that will reward and placate 
entrenched energy interests at the expense of conservation and 
development of renewable energy such as wind and solar said edwin 
rothschild energy policy director for citizen action a 
washingtonbased consumer advocacy group 
linda stuntz assistant undersecretary for policy and planning 
at the energy department said she expects the final plan to 
provide a balanced menu of both supply and demand proposals 
the energy strategy is hoped to allow bush to break the logjam 
for new energy initiatives in congress as he did in the area of new 
clean air legislation she suggested 
among proposals almost certain to be included in a final package 
are those aimed at streamlining regulations to ease the 
construction of nuclear power plants and the building of new 
natural gas pipelines officials say 
but some of the other proposals are thought less likely to 
survive 
these include a suggestion that congress impose a 
50centagallon gasoline tax set federal energy efficiency 
standards for new houses and require automakers to increase fuel 
economy of new cars to as much as 365 miles per gallon by the end 
of the decade 
to increase domestic energy production the proposals include 
tax credits for oil and gas drilling and opening federal lands 
including wilderness areas the arctic national wildlife refuge and 
parts of the outer continental shelf to energy exploration 
while those approaches have the administrations ear they are 
likely to meet strong opposition from environmentalists and 
lawmakers 
energy secretary james watkins made the national energy policy a 
priority when he took office in march 1989 the plan gained a fresh 
momentum after the iraq invaded kuwait on aug 2 
but ms stuntz expressed concern recently that public interest 
and political support for an energy program may wane once the gulf 
crisis and oil prices subside will the publics interest in a 
national energy policy remain the same if gasoline prices are back 
at 1 or so a gallon next summer she asked 
she and other energy department officials declined to discuss 
specific proposals although senior officials such as white house 
chief of staff john sununu have emphasized that the focus must be 
on measures driven by market forces and not new government 
regulations 
some of the options under consideration would require regulators 
to formally take energy impact into account whenever an agency 
considers new environmental regulations that may be viewed as 
attempts to bypass environmental requirements and reduce public 
oversight an energy department document 
among other proposals are 
an expansion of the gasguzzler tax on cars combined with a 
system of tax credits for buying fuelefficient vehicles 
incentives to promote alternative fuel vehicles including the 
government buying 60000 such vehicles and spending 10 billion 
over 10 years to establish 70000 retail alternative fuel outlets 
restructuring the utility industry to reduce the cost of 
electricity through increased competition 
</TEXT>
