<TEXT>
the federal railroad administration 
responding to a stream of sharp criticism from congressional 
investigators is redesigning its inspection system in an effort to 
assure the safety of us railways 
acknowledging deficiencies in the current inspection system fra 
administrator gilbert e carmichael said the changes will help 
assure continued public confidence in the safety of rail travel as 
the nation plans and builds a highspeed rail system 
the railroad administration has been the subject of four 
critical reports this year by the general accounting office the 
investigative arm of congress 
the reports requested by rep john dingell dmich chairman 
of the house energy and commerce committee concluded that the fra 
did not have enough hazardousmaterials inspectors and probably was 
deficient in other inspection areas 
these include inspections of track locomotive power and 
equipment operating practices and signal and train control 
in july the gao said the transportation department agency was 
not using available data to target routine inspections toward 
highrisk locations and toward railroads with poor safety records 
it said fra inspectors independently schedule their safety 
inspections without analyzing safety or accident data 
as a result railroads with increasing numbers of accidents 
did not receive additional inspection activity the gao said 
we found in many cases inspections decreased for railroads with 
increasing number of accidents 
the most recent gao report issued late last month took the 
review of the agency one step further 
fra does not know how many inspectors it needs to adequately 
cover the railroad industry the gao said fra does not 
know whether it has a sufficient number of safety inspectors to 
carry out its safety mission because fra has not developed 
inspection coverage standards 
carmichaels response is to redesign the inspection system a 
process he says will take 12 to 15 months 
at the end of that time id like to be able to say to the gao 
weve got the system in place go check it so congress will be 
comfortable and the public will be comfortable carmichael said 
at briefing last week 
dingell said that so far he is encouraged by the changes in a 
letter to transportation secretary samuel skinner he said i 
applaud the initiatives that you and gil carmichael have 
undertaken thus far to implement the recommendations 
carmichael said the changes are designed to improve the training 
of the 361 authorized federal inspectors and the 110 inspectors 
employed by state governments 
he said it also is aimed at ensuring that the inspectors are 
properly deployed that key areas such as the transport of 
hazardous materials are not neglected and that the statistics 
gathered to support the inspection system are timely complete and 
accurate 
carmichael said that when he became head of the fra at the 
beginning of the bush administration statistics were so poor that 
we didnt know exactly how many railroads there were in this 
country 
recordkeeping has improved and now he does there were 580 
railroads then now there are 605 an increase caused in part by 
large railroads spinning off their lines to small carriers 
perry rivkind carmichaels deputy said that when accidents at 
rail grade crossings and those involving trespassers on railroad 
property are discounted some 40 people a year lose their lives in 
railroad accidents 
compared with the 45500 killed in highway accidents in 1989 
alone it is obvious that railroads are an incredibly safe mode 
of transportation he said 
carmichael promised that statistics will be improved a 
comprehensive teaching and operations manual written for 
inspectors a training academy established standards for 
inspectors raised and the inspection staff kept at full strength 
through aggressive recruitment and hiring 
furthermore he said inspectors will be allocated to problem 
areas on a national basis previously he said the fra had a 
regional inspection plan with little uniformity on the national 
level or in the way the system dealt with problem areas 
carmichael said the transport of hazardous materials will get 
special priority although he stressed there has been no fatal 
accident in that area since 1980 
i live with a bhopal in the back of my mind he said 
referring to the december 1984 chemical leak at a union carbide 
pesticide plant at bhopal india that killed 3403 people and 
injured 20000 
</TEXT>
