<TEXT>
third world countries foreign debt rose to 
1096 trillion this year up from 1051 trillion last year and 
from 786 billion in 1984 the central intelligence agency reports 
the figure does not include the soviet union china and other 
countries either still under communist rule or emerging from it 
such as those in eastern europe those countries add at least 
another 210 billion according to earlier estimates by the cia and 
the world bank 
the money is owed to more affluent governments including the 
united states japan and west germany to their private commercial 
banks and to intergovernmental bodies like the world bank another 
29 billion owed to the international monetary fund is listed 
separately 
although the cia reported a rise of 45 billion in the debt 
since last year it showed that payments dropped to 122 billion 
from the 126 billion of 1989 
for the debtors the payment level is more important than debt 
itself each dollar they save on payments to their creditors is a 
dollar they can spend on new foreign goods 
they can use foreign goods either to raise their peoples living 
standards or to invest in new equipment that will produce more 
goods and jobs for their rapidly rising work force 
the cia handbook includes information compiled from the world 
bank and the international monetary fund in washington the 
organization for economic cooperation and development in paris and 
the bank for international settlements in basel switzerland 
the book consists only of tables and does not explain the rise 
and fall of figures 
of the 113 countries listed the heaviest debt is reported for 
brazil 115341 billion up from 11215 billion in 1989 brazil 
also owes about 8 billion in back interest but the cia does not 
include such arrears in its figures they show brazil as paying 
101 billion on its debt this year compared with 119 billion 
last year and 161 billion the year before 
the new government of president fernando collor de mello is deep 
in negotiations with private banks to which it owes the bulk of 
its debt they are urging at least some payments on the back 
interest 
mexicos debt of 8802 billion is the second largest reduced 
under the plan of treasury secretary nicholas f brady last year 
it was 90789 billion mexicos payments also have dropped due to 
the new arrangement to 1006 billion this year from last years 
13104 billion 
