scientists say pictures of the far side 
of the moon taken by the spacecraft galileo will help fill a blank 
spot on the map of the planet 
the pictures taken as galileo sped past the moon and earth on 
its sixyear voyage to jupiter also should reveal more about the 
mineral content of the moons crust scientists said monday 
were actually doing some new observation said james head 
a member of galileos imaging team at nasas jet propulsion 
laboratory 
the national aeronautics and space administration displayed 
black and white photos of the full moon that provided a sharp image 
of the orientale basin as well as portions of both the near and far 
sides of the moon 
the spacecraft swung into the earths gravitational field 
saturday hurtling 597 miles above the western atlantic at the 
point of its closest approach 
by sweeping near earth galileo was able to use gravitational 
pull like a slingshot to increase its speed by 11600 mph boosting 
its velocity to 79000 mph in relation to the sun 
galileos approach allowed scientists to focus the crafts 
cameras on the far side of the moon for the first exploration of 
the region since nasas apollo missions in the 1970s 
the cameras photographed a wedge of moonscape near the south 
pole on the far side that somehow was missed by previous us and 
soviet mapping missions said project scientist torrence johnson 
thats interesting its got craters just like the rest of the 
moon but theres no great scientific surprise in that johnson 
said 
a subsequent journey through the earths magnetic field gave 
scientists their first measurements of a solar storm in which 
magnetically charged ions take on higher energy levels 
the data could reveal whether the majority of these ions which 
trigger colorful auroras near earths magnetic poles come from the 
sun or earth said lou frank chairman of galileos magnetic field 
working group 
