quayle complained that the first three witnesses before the 
senate armed services committee early this month all were critical 
of bush policy nunn chairman of that committee is a fixture on 
the list of potential democratic challengers for the white house 
sen albert gore jr dtenn who sought the nomination in 1988 
and says he is considering it again is a committee member 
they have been among the critics of bushs decision to double 
the us force arrayed against iraq opening the possibility of 
offensive action to drive saddam hussein out of occupied kuwait 
democratic congressional leaders decided on hearings instead of 
calling congress back into session to consider legislation on us 
policy bush had said that was alright with him he also has said 
he would welcome congressional backing for his course quayle told 
the governors the prospect of recalling congress posed a dilemma 
because there is no perceived consensus 
i cannot predict with any certainty what they will do when 
they get back in january he said 
retired military and government officials at the armed services 
committee hearings and at companion hearings of the senate foreign 
relations committee recommended a goslow course in the gulf 
crisis one in which the usled alliance against saddam hussein 
would wait for economic sanctions to take their full toll on iraq 
but quayle said waiting 12 to 18 months would be unacceptable 
patience at any price would be a failed policy he said 
amounting to appeasement of saddam quayle said the iraqi president 
is trying to use congress and american public opinion in a 
political war to deprive the administration of its option to use 
force 
it wont work he said because despite the efforts of some in 
congress the fact of the matter is that the american people 
support the president quayle added that in the end when 
americas vital interests are on the line the majority of congress 
can rise above partisan politics 
but he argued that is not happening now 
a congress solidly united behind the president would 
strengthen the chances for peace quayle said 
unfortunately by portraying themselves as the party of peace 
and the administration as the party of war some congressional 
democrats but by no means all congressional democrats seem to 
have placed partisanship above statesmanship he said 
</TEXT>
