the new chairman of the house science 
committee said tuesday that americas space station will be pushed 
into the next century if the broad changes sought by the 
administrations space advisory panel are implemented 
rep george brown dcalif called mondays recommendations of 
the advisory committee on the future of the us space program a 
reasoned balanced report both brown and his senate counterpart 
al gore dtenn plan hearings in january on the study 
commissioned by nasa and the white house 
the report recommended that reliance on the space shuttle be 
reduced and that plans for space station freedom be scaled down 
both in scope and mission it said too that nasa should 
concentrate on science not engineering spectaculars 
nasa already had switched orbital delivery of some cargoes from 
the space shuttle to unmanned singleuse rockets and most of the 
future shuttle missions are dedicated to science 
the sixth and last flight of 1990 landed in california early 
tuesday after nine days of astronomical observations with four 
telescopes it was the 13th mission since flight resumed in 1988 
nasa has scheduled seven flights in 1991 
brown elected by the house democratic caucus last week as 
chairman of the committee on science space and technology said 
that while the space future report is a good approach i lament 
that we are still in stage of going through reports 
reevaluations and redirections when the space program deserves 
stability and adequate resources 
in passing the nasa budget for 1991 congress also demanded that 
the space station be made smaller and less costly a move also 
recommended by the space future panel nasa is in the midst of a 
90day period of drawing up new designs 
another restructuring of the space station is going to make it 
impossible to maintain the present schedule brown said it 
probably means we wont even get started on building the station 
until the latter years of the 90s and there will be no occupancy 
until the 21st century 
the first shuttle flight to put hardware for the station into 
orbit had been scheduled for 1995 and the station was to have been 
permanently manned well before the year 2000 
this further complicates relationships with our partners in 
the station the japanese europeans and canadians who need to be 
fully involved and have to modify their own participation as a 
result of any changes we make brown said 
the next shuttle mission to deploy unclassified payloads for 
the air force and the strategic defense organization is planned 
for late february or early march a welcome hiatus to crews that 
had to handle three flights in as many months 
after these three i think christmas is going to be a real 
nice break said flight director bob castle well come back 
from christmas and be ready to go 
the planned 1991 missions include an april trip in which the 
gamma ray observatory is to be carried into orbit and in may a 
space life sciences laboratory is to ride aboard columbia 
discovery is to fly in july with another in a series of tracking 
and data relay satellites which gather information from other 
satellites and space shuttles and send it to the ground 
atlantis is to fly in august with several defense department 
payloads on a mission lasting 10 days discovery is scheduled again 
in november with the upper atmosphere research satellite and the 
final launch is that of atlantis in december carrying a manned 
scientific laboratory in its cargo bay 
the space future committee was headed by norman r augustine a 
veteran aerospace executive who is chairman and ceo of the martin 
marietta company 
commenting on the report nasa administrator richard truly 
pointed out that despite leaks that grounded the shuttle and flaws 
in the hubble space telescope nasa has averaged one launch in 
every two months since shuttles returned to flight in 1988 
he said it will not be difficult to adopt many of the 
recommendations in the report 
frankly i believe we are exactly in line with the augustine 
report and with congress he said 
