<TEXT>
from politicians in chartered planes to 
peasants on horseback thousands have converged on this village 
deep in the amazon for a murder trial that some say could shape the 
future of the worlds largest rain forest 
two cattle ranchers accused of killing union leader and renowned 
amazon defender chico mendes are expected to go on trial beginning 
wednesday nearly two years after mendes was gunned down 
but already the village of pastelcolored wood cabins about 
2650 miles miles northwest of rio de janeiro is buzzing with 
speculation and a sense of fear over the final judgment 
local residents many of whom survive by harvesting rubber and 
nuts from the forest see the trial as symbolizing the battle 
between the poor seeking collective use of the rain forest against 
landowners and ranchers who want to cut it down 
private and government development efforts in the amazon region 
have intensified since 1980 and estimates on deforestation range 
from from about 5 percent to 12 percent the rain forest about 
twice the size of alaska is the only habitat for many of the 
