agency spokesman al heier said the animals were absorbing the 
pesticides into their skins and suffered tremors vomiting and 
convulsions young kittens and old cats were the most susceptible 
but often recovered if they were bathed he said 
the illinoisbased national animal poison information network 
told epa that by the end of 1987 the year the product went on the 
market it had reports of 496 incidents including 75 deaths 
heier said 
harrison njbased hartz mountain placed warnings on its 
labels in 1987 then voluntarily removed the product in 1988 to 
conduct more extensive testing heier said blockade was 
reintroduced in 1989 
epa did not bring its formal 18count complaint until jan 31 
hartz spokesman william pearlberg said the company was most 
surprised at the complaint believing it had reported all 
required information in a timely manner 
registered pesticide producers must pass on health complaints to 
epa within a reasonable period epa defined that as a month in 
the blockade case epa attorney scott garrison said 
we did not consider it to be reporting when we had to send 
inspectors out to get it garrison said 
heier said blockade flea and tick repellents contain a 
combination of the pesticides deet and fenvalerate 
there is some danger in the product heier said however 
from our information it shows the risks of using blockade is no 
greater than using any other pet product 
according to heier the revised label directs consumers not to 
use blockade on cats less than a year old on pregnant cats or on 
puppies younger than 3 months 
hartz mountain maintains the formula is effective in preventing 
insectborne diseases 
 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

