<TEXT>
pfizer inc will conduct an unprecedented 
search to warn about 23000 patients about rare but often fatal 
fractures of an implanted heart valve officials said tuesday 
the food and drug administration said it had accepted pfizers 
plan to locate patients who have the bjorkshiley 60degree 
convexoconcave heart valve 
valve fractures have occurred in about seven of every 10000 
patients per year the fda said 
the valve was implanted in about 82000 people worldwide between 
1979 and november 1986 when it was removed from the market about 
23000 of the patients who are still alive are in the united states 
and canada 
about 295 fractures of the valve were reported to the fda with 
178 deaths resulting 
when a valve fractures a patients life can be saved if the 
valve is replaced quickly 
thats why it is important for cc valve patients to ask their 
doctors how to recognize early signs of valve fracture and what to 
do should it occur fda deputy commissioner james benson said 
public citizen health research group a ralph naderfounded 
advocacy group has been pressing the fda and pfizer for years to 
notify patients about the danger 
the fdas procedure has been for companies recalling medical 
devices to contact physicians who then would speak to their 
patients but that policy is being reviewed said fda spokeswoman 
susan cruzan 
also the agency is developing a plan to work with foreign 
governments to notify patients overseas she said about 59000 
patients with the valve live outside north america 
the company last week sent letters to about 19000 heart 
specialists telling them of the program and asking them to contact 
patients who have the shiley valve about 450 hospitals are also 
being contacted 
on thursday the company will announce plans for a patient 
registry that will include a tollfree telephone number for 
patients to identify themselves 
