workers stepped over spilled cargo from trucks as well as scattered 
luggage and clothing thrown from cars 
and the survivors marveled at their own good fortune amid the 
carnage that surrounded them 
mary youness 55 of cleveland and her family were next to a 
propane tanker truck when the accident began they heard crashes 
all around in the fog she said but their car managed to slide 
onto the shoulder unscathed 
we feel terribly lucky this truck was on the other side of 
us and a car was smashed between this truck and another truck 
mrs youness said 
and the truck driver said that if the car had not been between 
them a girl was killed in the car that was between if the other 
truck had hit him this explosion of propane would have wiped 
everything out she said 
officials feared the death toll the worst since the state began 
keeping records 20 years ago still could mount as rescue workers 
searched the remains of some of the vehicles 
but there were also tales of heroism 
bill johnson 45 was headed south on interstate 75 about 930 
am when his citizens band radio started crackling that there was 
trouble ahead on the fogshrouded highway 
everybody was hollering on the cbs set it down johnson 
said i stopped because i could see the tail lights of the truck 
ahead but when i stopped another one hit me in the back 
johnson said he got out of his pickup and rushed to check on the 
two people in the vehicle behind him a fourwheel drive truck the 
driver was shaken up he said 
i said are you all right and he said buddy i dont 
know i said will you please just get out of your truck he 
said i dont know i said please get out of your truck 
johnson said 
both people got out and johnson and the driver walked around 
back of the fourwheel drive vehicle seconds later a rental truck 
rushed out of the fog and crashed into the rear of the second 
vehicle turning it into an unrecognizable heap of metal 
thats how quick it hit johnson said shaking his head 
we got right by that before he hit this is the worst thing 
ive ever seen 
the people who left with rescue workers before johnson got 
their names were frightened but unhurt 
they didnt get a scratch johnson said 
