the publisher of the new york daily news on 
tuesday claimed progress in regaining circulation lost in a nearly 
7weekold strike and said the tabloid isnt ready to cut losses 
and sell 
publisher james hoge met with the board of directors of the 
tribune co which owns the daily news to discuss the strike as 
about 100 prounion pickets marched outside the landmark tribune 
tower 
the strike is costly but not as expensive as trying to run the 
paper with all the excess costs and contract abuses that we had 
in the old contract hoge told a news conference 
a spokesman for nine striking unions said the daily news cant 
hope to survive without a settlement or sale of the newspaper 
our rule is that we are plowing ahead as long as we can show 
that we are making significant progress hoge said of putting out 
the newspaper under strike conditions it is the opinion of 
everyone involved in this process that we are making significant 
progress and we are going forward 
the newspaper has published every day since the strike began 
oct 25 but circulation dropped from 109 million hoge said net 
paid circulation was up this week to 580000 copies from 552000 a 
week ago 
hoge attributed the increase to a network of news dealers and 
hawkers that now total nearly half the prestrike number of 12000 
outlets 
hoge said he was confident that advertisers who bailed out of 
the daily news would return to the newspaper as circulation 
increases 
the striking unions representing 2100 workers claim unfair 
labor practices the daily news has hired replacement workers to 
put out the newspaper 
on wednesday negotiations switch for the first time to 
washington before the federal mediation and conciliation service 
the two sides were to meet separately with a mediator 
