<TEXT>
in a season of selfconsciously serious films mermaids is a 
refreshing breather a bittersweet reminiscence of one familys 
chaotic comingofage in the 1960s 
the holiday treat in mermaids is the addition of another 
memorable portrait by cher in the gallery of women shes portrayed 
on screen the entertainer who once had trouble being accepted as 
a serious actress has matured into a powerful movie presence with 
a gift for showing the soft center of tough women without getting 
gooey about it 
in mermaids cher is mrs flax a woman on the run from her 
own personal demons who takes her two young daughters along for the 
ride she wears tight dresses tends to bed the wrong men and when 
it all falls apart as it does every few months she packs up her 
girls and hits the road choosing a new town by poking her finger 
at a map 
for teenage daughter charlotte who narrates this story these 
moves are a recurring nightmare although not catholic she 
retreats into fantasies about being a nun charlotte portrayed by 
the ubiquitous winona ryder who seems to be in every movie 
requiring a teenager this season fashions a shrine in her room 
and sees all events as signs from god 
her young halfsister kate christina ricci is obsessed with 
competitive swimming and seems unfazed by the upheavals as long as 
theres a swimming pool in their new town 
we meet the fatherless flax family as mother is breaking up with 
another beau and moving on this time they settle in a picturesque 
new england village where the local shoe salesman bob hoskins 
takes a fancy to mrs flax charlotte meanwhile becomes smitten 
with the young handsome caretaker at the nearby convent 
challenging her vow to become a nun 
relationships develop and careen toward an unexpected crisis 
which seems too clearly a filmmakers technique for bringing the 
movie to a conclusion suspension of disbelief is essential here 
director richard benjamin deftly uses the splendid new england 
scenery and the 60s backdrop to draw mrs flaxs world the songs 
of the era are sprinkled throughout and a segment recalling the 
john f kennedy assassination is poignantly evocative of a calamity 
seen through the eyes of a teenager 
it seemed there were no adults alive anymore charlotte 
muses as she walks the empty leafstrewn streets in that autumn of 
1963 
winona ryders earnestness is appealing and hoskins exuding 
warmth and normalcy is the perfect foil for chers brassy mrs 
flax 
some will be reminded of chers tough but caring mother in 
mask but mrs flax is her own woman cher knows her well and 
insists that we like her how can we resist 
mermaids is rated pg13 with a nonexplicit sex scene and 
discussions of sex but no objectionable language 
equals 
motion picture association of america rating definitions 
g general audiences all ages admitted 
pg parental guidance suggested some material may not be 
suitable for children 
pg13 special parental guidance strongly suggested for 
children under 13 some material may be inappropriate for young 
children 
r restricted under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult 
guardian 
nc17 no one under 17 admitted 
