<TEXT>
federal authorities unsealed a 42count 
indictment tuesday charging six men with operating a 21 million 
investment and insurance scam that left more than 1300 families 
with no health insurance coverage 
the grand jury indictment resulted from a twoyear investigation 
by the fbi the internal revenue service and inspectors from the 
us postal service and the department of labor 
what is especially frightening is that we all can be 
victimized by this type of criminal enterprise because each of us 
has a very fundamental need for a health insurance policy that will 
assure us and our families that we can afford the health care we 
may need said julian de la rosa inspector general with the 
labor department 
he spoke at a news conference at the federal courthouse in 
charlotte 
there are more than 1350 victims that have been identified in 
this one investigation de la rosa said but the tragedy is not 
confined to these 1350 unfortunate people 
the indictment describes allegations of fraud by the nowdefunct 
cap staffing of charlotte a firm which leased employees to more 
than 120 firms the company was to use fees paid by the firms to 
provide health insurance and other benefits to the workers 
but the indictment said the companys managers used the funds 
for themselves 
the companies that used cap staffing are in north carolina 
south carolina georgia virginia kentucky ohio pennsylvania and 
illinois the indictment said 
the issue of such health insurance scams was the subject of a 
hearing last spring in the us senate and de la rosa said his 
office is investigating about three dzen similar schemes 
the victims number in the tens of thousands with unpaid 
medical claims totaling in the tens of millions of dollars he 
said 
six men were arrested tuesday robert w long victor s 
blackwell and jerry m wolicki of charlotte david r harris of 
greenville sc michael a krebser of stuart fla and michael 
h spieles of palm city fla 
in an accompanying civil action officials also seized seven 
homes 26 vehicles and business and personal bank accounts from the 
men the property was worth 3 million officials said 
long and blackwell made short court appearances tuesday morning 
where they were released on bond said us attorney tom ashcraft 
ashcraft said the seized assets would be used to help the 
victims of the scam but it would be a mistake to think there is 
a big pot of gold out there 
de la rosa said the biggest tragedy was that many of the victims 
were left uninsurable 
this has had a catastrophic effect on many of these people who 
have been refused expensive and medically necessary care because 
they lack health insurance and they may never be able to obtain it 
for any preexisting conditions de la rosa said 
the charges listed in the indictment include mail fraud money 
laundering embezzlement and conspiracy 
