<TEXT>
the ruling communist party in albania 
the last country practicing stalinism in europe on tuesday decided 
to allow the formation of other political parties the state news 
agency ata said 
the surprise announcement in the country of 31 million 
residents was made in a communique released after a meeting of the 
partys policysetting central committee in the capital of tirana 
the plenum was of the opinion that the creation of independent 
political organizations according to the law in force is to the 
good of the further democratization of the life of the country and 
pluralism the ata report said 
the balkan nation which opened its borders slightly this year 
after decades of isolationism under the late enver hoxha would be 
the last country in europe to introduce a multiparty system 
albania broke relations with the soviet union in 1961 over 
hoxhas stalinist and prochinese policies sixteen years later 
albania severed ties with the chinese 
albania has scheduled elections for feb 10 they are seen as a 
test of the governments willingness to live up to pledges of 
gradual reform and of the peoples ability to exercise a measure of 
political freedom after decades of authoritarian rule 
but it was not immediately clear if there will be enough time 
for new political parties to form and compete in the elections 
the central committee meeting was held following student unrest 
that started this weekend and continued tuesday with a protest of 
between 2000 and 3000 students 
ata said the central committee also fired five full members and 
two candidate members of the politburo and called on premier adil 
carcani to make the necessary changes in his government 
yugoslav and other observers believed the politburo reshuffle 
and the call for the creation of independent parties amounted to a 
defeat of the hardliners led by nexhmie hoxha 69 widow of hoxha 
who died five years ago 
it scheduled an party congress for june 1991 and a national 
party meeting on dec 26 to define the electoral platform of the 
party and endorse the list of its candidates for deputies to the 
peoples assembly 
earlier tuesday students demanded communist authorities provide 
more heat and light for their dormitories 
president ramiz alia has conceded albanias economy was on the 
brink of a state of emergency a severe drought has curbed power 
supplies most of albanias power comes from hydroelectric plants 
the students gathered outside their rooms in tirana and stayed 
away from classes on tirana universitys campus on the edge of the 
city diplomats in tirana said 
the diplomats speaking on condition of anonymity said police 
were out in force apparently to keep the students away from the 
public no violence or arrests were reported 
on sunday several students were hurt and detained in clashes 
with clubwielding police diplomats said 
ata monitored in vienna took the unusual step of reporting 
unrest on sunday and monday 
alia met with student representatives late tuesday and urged 
them to return to classes or else incidents which nobody desires 
could occur 
according to radio tirana monitored in london alia told the 
students that top national leaders had followed the protests and 
from the beginning had expressed themselves in favor of dialogue 
the students told alia their idea of creating an independent 
political organization of students and young intellectuals and 
alia said they could submit their demand for registration to the 
ministry of justice 
the government acted relatively swiftly to defuse a political 
crisis in july when thousands of albanians streamed into foreign 
embassies in tirana taking refuge until being allowed to emigrate 
since then the communist leadership which has tinkered with 
economic and political reform following eastern europes 1989 
revolutions has come under further pressure with the defection of 
ismail kadare the countrys greatest writer he fled in october 
saying his hopes that alia could become albanias mikhail gorbachev 
had been dashed 
