<TEXT>
western embassies and aid organizations 
are urging their nationals to leave somalia where banditry 
rebellions and an accelerating breakdown of law and order put life 
at risk 
roughly 50 or more westerners left the capital mogadishu since 
last weekend following directives from the us british and german 
embassies and the un high commissioner for refugees 
the foreigners left a city beset by a steep increase in poverty 
and street crime violence from security forces an advancing rebel 
army and a collapsing economy observers say president mohammed 
siad barre faces the greatest threat to his 21year rule 
its a terrible situation said a western diplomat who 
monitors somalia for his mission it has all the classic signs of 
a regime on its last legs 
he spoke on condition of anonymity 
since june six or more unexplained bombings hit diplomatic 
missions and government offices and at least three foreigners died 
in robberies holdups and car thefts 
in july security forces fired on a soccer stadium crowd who 
jeered the president killing at least 60 people diplomats say in 
july the red beret presidential guard seized at least 36 
fourwheel drive vehicles at gunpoint from western organizations 
the fanatically loyal red beret battalion drawn from siad 
barres marehan subclan guards him around the clock he had a 
bunker built at mogadishus international airport which doubles as 
an air force base diplomats say he has been known to spend time 
there it affords a quick escape route by air 
