<TEXT>
david lodge is on his first american publicity 
tour and the english author seems a little dazed 
blame some of it on jet lag the rest on culture shock when his 
first novel came out in 1962 writers didnt give interviews in 
fact lodge waited years before he even had a public reading 
but hell have to adjust this mildmannered author is now 
somewhat a celebrity his claim to fame is such gently mischievous 
novels as changing places small world and nice work 
which has just been issued in paperback 
these stories always have two sides men vs women religion 
vs secularism america vs england and lodge is the referee 
laying down the rules and calmly watching from the sidelines as 
characters collide and opinions crumble 
the very first novel i published the picturegoers is about 
an agnostic boy and a catholic girl and as a result of their 
relationship she becomes agnostic and he becomes religious lodge 
said relaxing in an armchair in his manhattan hotel room 
because i dont have very strong political or idealistic ideas 
to put forth myself i find it easy to put forth novels of 
contrasting views i also find it humorous working on a level 
where everybody understands the rules and obeys them 
lodge born in 1935 grew up in southeast london his childhood 
was often grim and as he writes in the introduction to out of 
the shelter an autobiographical novel his irreverent sense of 
humor was shaped by air raids and postwar austerity 
in nice work the author toys with the stuffy victor wilcox 
and the overeducated robyn penrose throwing them together in an 
uneasy merger of the smokestack and the ivory tower 
wilcox is the manager of an engineering firm his quest for 
identity reaching no further than his resume penrose who teaches 
classes on 19th century industrial novels would rather read about 
factories than actually visit them 
lodge takes these imaginary creatures and sets them in a cage 
called rummidge an english city that occupies for fictional 
purposes the space where birmingham is to be found on maps of 
the socalled real world 
the year is 1986 the government has proclaimed it industry 
year and a university panel has developed an industry year 
shadow scheme a faculty member is to shadow a senior 
management employee in local manufacturing robyn gets the 
assignment her subject naturally is victor 
heres a boymeetsgirl story set against the background of a 
citys crumbling economy victor pompous and materialistic finds 
himself falling in love with this attractive independent woman 
robyn is horrified by her initial exposure to the luecollar 
world but slowly realizes machines and assembly lines are no less 
important than analyses of jane austen 
an encounter is inevitible and lodge keeping the sex safe 
writes with the detached amusement of a nosy neighbor whose ear is 
pressed against the wall 
robyns mood is blythe she feels mildly wanton but not 
wicked she sees herself as not seducing vic but as putting him out 
of his misery perhaps she feels a certain sense of triumph at 
her conquest the captain of industry at the feet of the feminist 
literary critic a pleasing tableau 
for vic the event is indefinitely more momentous his mood 
infinitely more perturbed the prospect of going to bed with robyn 
penrose is the secret dream of weeks come true he regards 
himself with wonderment led by the hand by this handsome young 
woman toward her bedroom as if his soul is stumbling along out of 
step behind his body 
the scene where they actually go to bed together i must have 
written about 10 times it took a lot of thinking explained 
lodge who in 1987 retired as a professor at the university of 
birmingham 
robyn is far more serious even questioning the very idea of 
novels which she attacks as capitalist tools the message of the 
novel is clear she states the alienation of work under 
industrial capitalism can be overcome by an infusion of loving 
kindness and imaginative play 
thats going too far for lodge feminism is up for grabs so are 
religion and politics but the author doesnt mind sounding a 
little dogmatic about writing the only time hes willing to 
solemnly bow his head and offers thanks to a power greater than his 
own 
we learn how to negotiate our lives through novels lodge 
said we learn about experiences beyond our own a novel is not 
the only form that does that but i still think its the most 
versatile of all forms you dont need much money all you need as 
a writer is a pad and a pen 
when you get to my stage of life you dont ask yourself why 
you write its sort of what youve become youre a novelist its 
like being a professional golfer 
