<TEXT>
liberalconservative barricades within the 
nations churches have limited religious groups ability to help 
americans develop a common ground to discuss moral issues the 
third installment of a fourpart series unholy wars religion in 
public life examines the consequences 
 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
religion in america was simpler in the 1950s 
the phrase under god was added to the pledge of allegiance 
catholics evangelicals jews and muslims kept a low profile and a 
pecking order helped a communitys most prominent citizens 
gravitate toward mainline protestant institutions such as the 
presbyterian and episcopal churches 
but then a series of sociological changes shook nearly 3 
centuries of protestant hegemony ranging from the rapid rise of 
evangelicalism to the surge of catholics to equal protestants in 
income and education to judicial rulings limiting the influence of 
religion in public life 
in explaining what happened in his midwest community one 
mainline protestant executive told hartford seminary dean william 
mckinney you have to understand the neighborhood changed when 
the whites moved out and the irish catholics moved in 
the demographic shifts have not led to a passive changing of the 
guard but to what some observers see as increasingly bitter 
divisions between liberals and conservatives that threaten 
religions traditional role of supplying society with a common set 
of moral standards 
religious people have got to get their act together said 
dean thomas ogletree of yale divinity school if were unable to 
talk to one another because were so divided the larger society is 
wise to say lets keep religion out of it because theyll just 
mess it up 
in a 1984 gallup poll 31 percent of religious conservatives 
held negative stereotypes of religious liberals while only 7 
percent found similar faults with themselves the range of 
intolerance was even greater on the religious left where 41 
percent held negative views of conservatives while only 3 percent 
said liberal sterotypes were valid 
the division is at least as strong if not stronger than it 
was five years ago said robert wuthnow a princeton university 
sociology professor who has studied the issue 
america may be heralded as a haven for religious freedom but it 
also has a history of religious bigotry 
at the founding of the country most states had laws 
discriminating against catholics and formally establishing either 
anglican or congregational churches 
strong anticatholic and antisemitic attitudes existed into the 
1950s despite a veneer of placid tolerance epitomized by president 
eisenhowers declaration that our government makes no sense 
unless it is founded on a deeply felt religious faith and i dont 
care what it is 
but the 60s and 70s saw unprecedented ecumenical advances 
fueled by such things as a broad range of religious groups working 
together on the civil rights movement pope john xxiii opening the 
windows of the catholic church to the world with the second vatican 
council and a series of theological statements from christian 
groups apologizing for their past antisemitism 
i think if you look at any long time line the trend is only 
up said jacqueline wexler president of the national conference 
of christians and jews 
but many observers say the resurgence of catholics and 
bornagain christian evangelicals into the public arena has brought 
about a renewal of religious prejudice 
thirty percent of the respondents in a gallup survey last year 
said they would not welcome religious fundamentalists as neighbors 
by comparison only 5 percent said they would not welcome 
protestants in general or jews 
at a reformation day service in october at yale divinity school 
lutheran theologian george lindbeck lamented that anticatholicism 
has become in some corners the antisemitism of intellectuals 
mckinney who is studying mainline protestant executives and who 
authored american mainline religion its changing shape and 
future agreed 
i think anticatholicism is the last respectable american 
prejudice he said 
the liberalconservative barricades cross denominational lines 
many religious conservatives who tend to emphasize spirituality 
prayer and bible study over social concerns have begun to form 
their own organizations within mainline churches the good news 
movement in the united methodist church the presbyterian lay 
committee and the episcopal synod of america are examples 
in more conservative denominations such as the southern baptist 
convention those who favor greater acceptance of divergent 
theological views also have formed their own lobbying groups such 
as the southern baptist alliance 
but the liberalconservative divide may not be as wide as each 
side might think 
wuthnow said his research indicates conservatives are more 
tolerant and socially concerned than liberals think they are some 
conservative churches for example have established programs to 
help the homeless and counsel the unemployed 
in the brookings institution study religion in american public 
life a james reichley said many religious conservatives 
approach the abortion struggle with the same ardor liberals fought 
for civil rights 
on the issue of abortion they believe it is the liberals who 
are countenancing mass destruction of potential life while 
fundamentalists in alliance with catholics stand up for the most 
vulnerable of all forms of human life the unborn reichley 
said 
at the same time wuthnow said liberals are more devout in 
their faith than conservatives think they are as shown by a 
renewed interest in evangelism and bible study 
bishop herbert w chilstrom spiritual leader of the evangelical 
lutheran church in america said more than 9000 of the 
denominations 11000 congregations ordered tapes of a 
churchsponsored faithdevelopment program 
thats indicative of a very deep hunger for faith development 
among our people he said 
and partnerships are being fostered for the first time in a 
generation religious groups across the board now are forming 
coalitions on issues ranging from apartheid to pornography 
many religious leaders have a sense of being in the same boat 
they sense as they once did not the danger of religion being 
ttally driven out of a public role in society reichley said 
pressure has grown in recent years to consider issues ranging 
from abortion to nuclear war on secular grounds as more people 
view religion as a set of divisive sectarian interests wuthnow 
said 
when you take out the moral values supplied by religion he 
said then what becomes important are issues of economics 
political expediency practicality 
those are the wrong guidelines to use for deciding issues such 
as euthanasia genetic engineering allocation of limited health 
care resources and even whether the nation should go to war 
wuthnow and others said 
in the new religious climate the ability to compromise is seen 
as a high moral value said ogletree of yale divinity school 
the alternative to compromise is moral anarchy or religious 
conflict he said 
</TEXT>
