<TEXT>
a 101 billion privatization of britains 
electricity industry was a huge success the government said with 
britons seeking more than 10 times the number of shares being 
offered 
demand from the public was so strong in fact that it triggered 
a clawback mechanism that scaled back the amount of shares 
reserved for both foreign investors and domestic institutional 
investors said kleinwort benson ltd the governments financial 
advisor 
kleinwort said monday the offer was 107 times oversubscribed by 
the general public 
under the offering the government sold a total 216 billion 
shares in the 12 electricity distributing companies of england and 
wales the shares sold for 240 pence or 468 each for a total 
518 billion pounds 101 billion 
the government plans to sell its two electricity generating 
companies and the scottish electricity industry next year 
the selloff is britains biggest and most complex privatization 
yet the conservative government has sold 64 billion worth of 
stateowned companies over the past decade to promote capitalism 
and encourage wider ownership of the companies 
the privatizations include telephone gas and water utilities 
as well as british airways plc british aerospace plc and the 
automaker jaguar plc which has since been bought by ford motor co 
critics had questioned the governments timing of its latest 
sale noting that many investors have shied away from the stock 
market since the aug 2 iraqi invasion of kuwait they also cite 
the worldwide economic slowdown 
the government had planned to cancel the sale if a war broke out 
in the persian gulf 
but kleinwort said it received 1275 million applications from 
individual investors the highest response ever for a government 
privatization 
energy secretary john wakeham said only about 25 percent of the 
applicants will receive all the shares they requested and many 
investors will receive only the minimum 100 shares because of the 
huge demand 
he said some shares will go to about 97 percent of the 
applicants who are electricity customers while twothirds of all 
applicants will receive some shares 
officials noted the clawback provision will boost the 
percentage of shares available to the public to 546 percent from 
344 percent british institutional investors will now get 304 
percent of shares and foreign investors will receive 15 percent 
shares will begin trading tuesday afternoon analysts are 
predicting prices will jump 40 percent to 50 percent when trading 
begins 
the london stock exchange plans to remain open an extra 90 
minutes tuesday to accommodate anticipated heavy dealing 
there might very well be a scramble tomorrow afternoon for the 
shares among institutions that saw their allocations scaled back 
said sean darby an analyst at the investment firm yamaichi 
international europe ltd 
the government has made sure that everybody has got something 
but basically they kept it down to the lowest rung he said 
