<TEXT>
advertising spending is expected to grow next 
year at the slowest pace in more than two decades but should pick 
up along with the economy in 1992 a prominent industry forecaster 
says 
some analysts say the forecast may be too optimistic while 
other executives expressed reservations about whether the economy 
will improve as expected in the second half of 1991 
robert coen an executive at the ad agency mccannerickson said 
monday he expects us ad spending will rise 49 percent to 1301 
billion this year the smallest increase since 48 percent in 1975 
next year he said spending should grow 46 percent to 136 
billion the smallest increase since a 07 percent increase in 
1970 
coen blamed the slowdown on the economic downturn and worries 
created by the persian gulf standoff newspapers are being 
especially hard hit 
coen whose semiannual forecasts of ad spending trends for the 
investment firm painewebber inc are the most closely watched in 
the industry has scaled back his estimate of ad spending growth 
for 1990 twice in the past year 
last december he said domestic ad spending would grow 62 
percent in 1990 he trimmed that projection to 53 percent last 
june 
coen said he is hopeful that improvements in the economy in the 
latter half of 1991 and the prospect of the olympic games could 
start another resurgence in ad spending in 1992 
he told the 18th annual painewebber media conference that 
national ad spending will rise 67 percent to 736 billion this 
year while local ad spending will increase a meager 28 percent to 
565 billion 
national ad spending is doing better than his december 1989 
forecast of a 63 percent increase but local ad spending has come 
in well below his earlier estimate of 62 percent growth 
he said newspapers for instance saw local ad spending grow at 
a slim 1 percent pace this year as spending by retailers slumped 
due to their heavy debt loads the poor business environment and 
deteriorating consumer confidence 
in addition he said the deepening decline in classified ad 
spending resulting from rising unemployment and a sluggish housing 
market made it a disastrous year for local ad spending in 
newspapers 
he expects only 2 percent growth in local ad spending in 
newspapers next year but added that a revival in the economy could 
lead to a fast turnaround 
national advertising on the other hand was stronger than 
expected this year partly because of increased competition for 
market share in categories such as coffee credit cards and mutual 
funds coen said 
for 1991 coen said he expects national ad spending will rise 
57 percent and local ad spending will increase 31 percent 
until unemployment rates fall and the real estate and housing 
sectors turn around we must continue to be pessimistic about local 
ad growth next year coen said 
gordon medenica vice president for corporate planning at the 
ew york times co said operating profits in the newspaper 
industry fell about 3 percent in 1990 and could fall another 2 to 4 
percentage points next year 
he said he was also a little worried about this consensus 
forecast that the economy will improve in the second half 
jack butcher circulation director at the tampa fla tribune 
said he expects the average cover price of newspapers will rise to 
35 cents daily and 1 on sundays in 1991 from their current levels 
of 30 cents and 75 cents 
but he said he expects the industry will still be able to show 
circulation growth of 05 percent to 1 percent because improvements 
such as more localized reporting better printing quality and color 
have been made 
