in a major step toward resolving the nations 
biggest product liability issue a federal judge has consolidated 
tens of thousands of lawsuits against a company filed by victims of 
asbestosrelated diseases 
us district judge jack b weinstein late monday certified a 
class action for 65000 worker health claims against eaglepicher 
industries inc and froze all litigation against the 
cincinnatibased industrial products maker 
but victims lawyers said weinstein had flouted legal procedure 
appointed partisan attorneys to negotiate with the company who 
supported his desires and sought to force a settlement they said 
was unfair 
the judges attitude is there is no constitution among 
friends said ron motley a charleston sc attorney for 
several thousands asbestos victims 
he was not acting as judge he was acting as king said fred 
baron a dallas plaintiffs lawyer fortunately in this country 
the laws are not determined by kings 
lawyers said they would appeal weinsteins order which also 
appeared to violate an automatic halt on legal proceedings in the 
case imposed when a motion was filed monday in cincinnati to place 
eaglepicher in involuntary bankruptcy 
if it succeeds weinsteins plan could become a model for dozens 
of companies struggling under the burden of asbestos liability and 
help clear state and federal courts nationwide of 90000 asbestos 
cases 
litigation has mounted since the early 1970s when medical 
evidence grew that asbestos was responsible for lung cancer and 
other respiratory diseases in americans who worked in shipbuilding 
boilermaking and other trades where the mineral was used as a fire 
retardant and insulator 
the biggest case involves the manville trust fund which faces 
130000 claims the fund has run out of cash and is being 
reorganized under weinsteins orders the trust was created out of 
the 1988 bankruptcy reorganization of manville corp once the 
nations largest asbestos user 
weinstein who crafted a classaction solution to illnesses 
caused by the vietnam war defoliant agent orange wants to 
consolidate asbestos cases to eliminate long and costly trials that 
have delayed payments to victims and squandered money on legal 
costs 
judge weinstein is out to break the logjam of national 
asbestos litigation by certifying the class which will be the 
beginning of the end of asbestos litigation said kenneth 
feinberg a weinsteinappointed mediator in the eaglepicher case 
eaglepicher which favors the class action has said it faces 
bankruptcy unless it solves its asbestos problems it is liable for 
injuries caused by cement insulation products containing asbestos 
it made from 1931 to 1971 
the company has spent 540 million in the last five years on its 
asbestos obligations and faces an estimated 600 million in future 
claims it has sold assets to pay claims but is running out of 
divisions to pawn as well as insurance the first case against the 
company was made in 1966 and about 20000 new claims are being 
filed annually 
under the settlement plan eaglepicher would place an estimated 
625 million into a trust fund over 20 years the trust also would 
receive 25 percent of eaglepicher stock and 50 percent if the 
company failed to meet its annual payments after five years 
payments would not begin until november 1993 
plaintiffs lawyers said the plan provides too little money and 
that victims would do better if eaglepicher filed for bankruptcy 
the main stumbling block appeared to be a demand that the trust 
control eaglepicher stock which the company refused 
only one of three lawyers appointed by weinstein to represent 
current eaglepicher victims has approved the plan and he doesnt 
have any asbestos clients more than 90 attorneys with 40000 
asbestos clients signed a petition opposing the proposal 
there is a massive lack of confidence in the settlement 
grant hering a new york plaintiffs lawyer told the judge for 
people who are victims who have suffered what they have suffered 
it is a gimmick they cant comprehend 
weinstein interrupted hearings on the plan in brooklyn federal 
court to certify the class action he froze all litigation 
involving eaglepicher pending a final settlement except for 
payment of 45 million in already negotiated claims 
the judge issued the order despite an automatic stay from the 
involuntary bankruptcy petition filing which he called 
fraudulent on its face the motion was filed at the behest of 
plaintiffs lawyers by three victims who said eaglepicher had not 
met settlement agreements 
in a statement eaglepicher called the bankruptcy petition 
totally without merit it said it did not believe the three 
victims had legal standing to file the petition 
weinstein appointed a former federal judge to study whether 
claimants would receive more money in a bankruptcy reorganization 
or the settlement he said hearings on the plans fairness would be 
held in new york cincinnati and detroit 
eaglepicher stock fell 75 cents to close at 325 monday on the 
new york stock exchange weinstein made his ruling after the 
markets closed 
