<TEXT>
the entrance of a general motors corp 
subsidiary into the race for the nextgeneration cellular phone 
technology will increase an industry fight over which system will 
prevail industry analysts say 
gm hughes electronics has developed technology it says will 
increase the capacity of cellular phone systems fifteenfold which 
would be a boon to overcrowded systems in cities such as new york 
and los angeles 
if theyre successful its going to bring the cellular 
industry to a big stall because people wont know what to do 
said john pemberton of the hightech research firm gartner group 
inc the standards battle could rage on for two years 
the cellular telecommunications industry association the 
industrys main trade group already has approved specifications 
for a digital technology that would replace todays analog cellular 
phones 
but the mostadvanced digital phone system envisioned by the 
trade group would only increase capacity six times below the 
tenfold increase the nations cellular phone operators say they 
will need to meet expected demand 
the trade group announced monday night that nine large cellular 
phone equipment makers agreed to a timetable for readying digital 
phone gear that uses the groups standard under it prototype 
equipment will be tested by march 31 meaning production should 
start later next year the group said 
the companies are motorola inc american telephone amp telegraph 
co ericsson audiovox mitsubishi novatel oki telecom sony and 
uniden 
hughes digital system to be formally announced today would 
provide much greater capacity than the systems to be tested it is 
based on the same technology called timedivision multiple access 
which allows several calls to be sent simultaneously over the same 
channel but hughes system is more advanced 
the timedivision technique introduces minute pauses into each 
call during these pauses another call in the cellular network is 
sent because the delays are so short and the call is sent in 
computer language the pauses are not noticed by the user 
but hughes system also uses pauses in conversations to send 
other calls said pradeep p kaul executive vice president of 
hughes network systems inc the hughes subsidiary that developed 
the system 
for example when a caller pauses in a conversation to listen to 
the other party the speaking portion of the signal would be 
switched off making it available for another call as soon as the 
caller resumes speaking a speachrecognition device would switch 
the signal back on 
hughes system will compete with a technology called 
codedivision multiple access in it several calls are sent at 
once over the same channel but each is preceded by a special code 
the receiving equipment only picks up calls with a particular code 
codedivision technology has been developed by a small san diego 
company called qualcomm atampt and motorola the two largest us 
makers of cellular telephone equipment are exploring qualcomms 
technology as well as timedivision techniques 
industry analysts say they believe timedivision technology will 
be used at least initially to boost the capacity of overtaxed 
cellular systems in major metropolitan areas 
but once the capacity of these timedivision systems is reached 
the industry will need yet another replacement said jason 
lamountain an analyst with the boston research firm yankee group 
inc 
he said hughes is one of a number of companies trying to boost 
timedivision technology to greater capacity at the same time 
codedivision technology will be vying for the replacement market 
he said proponents of this technology say it could boost capacity 
by twenty times over current analog systems 
as for the winner i think its going to be which one works 
none of them have been proven in the market lamountain said 
in another cellular development motorola said monday it had 
devised an enhanced analog system that increases capacity threefold 
over current systems it said it would began testing it in january 
hughes says it will use its technology to make the switching 
equipment used in each cell or geographic area of a cellular 
phone system and license the technology to other equipment makers 
it also said it would work with gms delco electronics corp to 
develop phones that would be built into the dashboards of cars 
in addition hughes announced that the french phoneequipment 
maker alactel would make the centraloffice phone switching 
equipment to be used with hughes cellular system 
