<TEXT>
dont bank on it but theres a possibility you 
might have a sizeable refund coming from your mortgage lender the 
result of errors in computing your adjustable rate payments 
while nobody knows the full extent of the computing errors the 
total is likely to be huge even in the billions of dollars 
refunding the money could become still another financial problem 
for already shaky lenders 
the first hint of errors came in the summer of 1989 when a 
former employee of the federal savings amp loan insurance corp 
studied portfolios of failed thrift institutions and found errors 
in a large percentage of mortgage loans 
seeking to determine the scope of the problem federal 
regulators already have asked lending institutions to audit their 
portfolios among these regulators were the federal reserve and the 
office of thrift supervision 
meanwhile a recent report from the general accounting office 
contains estimates that between 20 percent and 30 percent of all 
adjustable rate mortgages might have been calculated incorrectly 
for the most part assumptions to date are that the 
miscalculations were inadvertent rather than an attempt to defraud 
customers in fact it is likely that some errors favor borrowers 
rather than lenders 
why then have they occurred information to date suggests the 
answer lies in the complexity of caculations why didnt customers 
find the errors for the same reason complexity that caused 
lenders to make them 
hsh associates which tracks rates at institutions around the 
country and calls itself the nations largest publisher of mortgage 
information says errors could involve wrong dates wrong indexes 
and just poor arithmetic 
adjustable rate mortgages or arms are changed on a regular 
basis by rises or declines in an independent index such as the 
oneyear treasury bill rate or the sixmonth treasury bill 
rate or the eleventh district cost of funds 
most arms says hsh add a margin or markup to the index at 
each adjustment which might occur at six months or a year the 
resulting sum is then rounded to the nearest oneeighth percent 
some errors are likely to occur at this point but the 
possibilities for further errors are myriad some adjustments for 
example are limited up and down by caps that are written into the 
loan contracts 
hsh which has produced a booklet for homeowners wishing to 
check their arms lists a few of the other possibilities for error 
the servicer or company to which a borrower sends payments 
might select a monthly index value instead of a weekly one 
it might use the wrong date and thus the wrong index value 
an incorrect margin might be added to the index value in some 
cases the sum might not be rounded to the nearest oneeighth 
percent 
if the calculations are often too much for lenders and their 
computers how can a homeowner expect to do better the task is 
formidable to be sure and some people might automatically send 
the job to an accountant 
but say the folks at hsh it can be done by the homeowner with 
access to a newspaper and of course their handly little booklet 
and worksheet it is available for 3 from hsh associates 1200 
route 23 butler nj 07405 
theyll also calculate it for you if you tell them your current 
interest rate and send them a copy of your note rider or 
disclosure but itll cost you 25 
</TEXT>
