officer 
the conversion is allowed under a 1988 new york state law that 
is similar to other demutualization laws enacted in others states 
in recent years 
in an interview jenrette said the principal reason for 
demutualizing is to give the company more flexibility in raising 
capital but he denied that the equitable was in trouble 
the company is not in any jeopardy we are in strong financial 
shape he said 
another reason for demutualization he said is that it would 
give the company more flexibility as the financial services 
industry is deregulated as a mutual company the equitable cannot 
participate in transactions with shareholderowned companies 
due to the length of the conversion process he said the company 
may seek longterm private investors who in the meantime would 
purchase notes that could be converted into stock when the 
conversion is completed 
the equitable already has been in contact with several potential 
investors jenrette said declining to identify them 
frinquelli the salomon analyst speculated that japanese or 
european companies may be interested in taking a stake in the 
equitable to gain a foothold in the us insurance market jenrette 
said foreign investors were among those he has contacted 
the demutualization must be approved by state regulators and 
certain classes of policyholders 
the equitable started as a stock company in 1859 it was 
converted to a mutual company in 1918 under a plan devised by jp 
morgan amp co 
among its divisions is the stock brokerage donaldson lufkin amp 
jenrette inc which was cofounded by jenrette the equitable 
bought the brokerage in 1985 
the last insurance company of any size to demutualize was union 
mutual of portland maine which converted to a stockholder company 
in 1986 and now is called unum corp frinquelli said 
frinquelli added that if the equitable conversion is successful 
it could be the start of a trend 
