a federal judge approved a 67 million settlement 
between t boone pickens mesa limited partnership phillips 
petroleum co and phillips shareholders 
mesa phillips and other defendants agreed to pay the amount to 
settle the suit brought by shareholders unhappy with how phillips 
headed off pickens 1984 takeover bid 
us district judge murray m schwartz approved the settlement 
in wilmington del on monday and dismissed the case with 
prejudice which means it cannot be brought up again 
mesa will pay about 80 percent of the amount the settlement 
stipulates that the defendants make the payment without conceding 
guilt or wrongdoing 
in december 1984 mesa offered 60 a share in cash for up to 23 
million of phillips 1546 million outstanding common shares mesa 
was considering further shareholder enticements when it dropped the 
bid in an agreement with phillips which is based in bartlesville 
okla 
under the agreement mesa said it would sell back its 89 
million shares of phillips stock to the company for 53 a share in 
cash giving mesa a pretax profit of 89 million 
such a circumstance is sometimes considered greenmail in 
which a party threatens a takeover but profits by forcing the 
company to buy back its stock at a premium 
holders of phillips shares between dec 5 and dec 21 1984 
formed the class of plaintiffs in the suit 
