<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP901211-0257 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a major taiwanese investor has 
withdrawn from a 500 million petrochemical project that would have 
been the largest single foreign investment in the philippines since 
president corazon aquino took office in 1986 
the group said it pulled out of the project which has been 
mired in political controversy because of political unrest in the 
island nation 
butch pajarillo spokesman of the department of trade and 
industry said wednesday that the investor usi far east has 
written trade secretary jose concepcion notifying him of the firms 
pullout 
concepcions office received word of the pullout in a letter 
from anthony chong chairman of the taiwanese firm on monday 
in taipei usi far east spokesman lin yunteng confirmed the 
company has decided to withdraw 
we regret that we have to pull out the investment because of 
political reasons the petrochemical project is good for the 
industry and the philippine people lin said 
he said fighting between different political factions in the 
philippines led to the decision 
concepcion strongly supported the project saying it was crucial 
in building a petrochemical industry in a country struggling to 
cope with energy shortages but critics charged concepcion and 
others had been too generous in its financing arrangements 
the project became a major political controversy underscoring 
differences on investment policy within the aquino government 
supporters of the project said opposition would discourage 
foreign investment in the philippines whose economy is hobbled by 
a 28 billion foreign debt hard currency shortages and mounting 
inflation 
</TEXT>
